`repo.pushed_at` is updated by any push event — including force-pushes, branch deletions, wiki updates, and GitHub Actions workflow dispatches — and therefore does not reliably represent the date of the last source commit. Naming the field `lastCommitAt` sets a false expectation for downstream consumers (LLM prompt, issue body).

If the distinction matters, the accurate last-commit timestamp requires a separate API call (`GET /repos/{owner}/{repo}/commits?per_page=1`), which may be too expensive here. At minimum, consider renaming the field to `lastPushedAt` (or similar) so the semantics are clear and users are not misled when a repository's displayed "last commit" is actually a wiki push or bot-triggered ref update.","authorLogin":"greptile-apps","filePath":"src/sources/github.ts","lineStart":null,"lineEnd":null,"isGreptileComment":true,"addressed":false,"createdAt":"2026-03-05T10:04:14.127Z","hasSuggestion":false,"suggestedCode":null,"linkedMemory":null},{"id":"178960752","commentId":"PRRC_kwDORYuyec6sMkNl","body":"**`NOASSERTION` spdx_id not filtered**

